Question time, /hmofa/
How much exposition is too much?
I want to trim the boring fat from a story before calling it done, and I've read that if it isn't
1: summarizing a low-importance conversation
2: the narrator directly observing/reflecting on the action at a proportion that matches the current pace
3: worldbuilding that does not affect the pace (this includes any other description that is not tied to a character moving or interacting with other people or things)
then you should cut or move it.

My problem is that last one.
If I've made space in a conversation for a topic to be brought up organically, then one to three short to medium-length paragraphs of a first-person narrator filling the reader in on the world isn't bad, right?
Too short (because you diced it up into chunks) and now the reader has to work harder to get the picture you wanted. Too long, and the reader skips it, then complains later when the action needs them to remember it.

Or maybe I'm just overthinking this.

Anonymous Sun 02 Jan 2022 21:53:11 No.44433411 Report
Quoted By: >>44433643 >>44433968 >>44435120
>>44433027
>If I've made space in a conversation for a topic to be brought up organically, then one to three short to medium-length paragraphs of a first-person narrator filling the reader in on the world isn't bad, right?
The biggest thing for me is:
>What is the context behind the character listening to the exposition?
How much do they know about the world being presented? If they already know what’s being explained, then the conversation is completely useless. If you’re filling in just the reader, mitigate the exposition to just the important details. As interesting as your world may be, people don’t just wanna be told about it, they wanna experience it. Also don’t include too much exposition in your story. If you’re gonna do it now, limit it later on, because it gets very repetitive very quickly.
Generally, I try to avoid exposition dumps larger than a few sentences. Because as a reader, I rarely find them to be all that interesting. Also, I strongly recommend a beta reader, because another pair of eyes would be very helpful in finding that balance.

>>44435120
Let's try a slightly different perspective.

How large & intricate is the story? Are you comfortable with it's size? Do you think it cold be larger? Does it need to be smaller?

You used a subjective term of art when you said "cut the fat." It may not really be fat. You may have included what was necessary already/ When someone advises "cut the fat," keep in mind that means to evaluate if there is really any fat to cut. You may already have good balance for the story you're trying to tell, but it sounds like you want an outside opinion if your judgement is solid or not.

Maybe "the fat" is just concentrated in the wrong places and could use some light redistribution. Maybe the way yo present "the fat" could use a different approach, where you end up with a similar amount, but there's a better way.

Consider the total size of the story. Make a solid estimate of what you might cut and still tell the story. Now, what is the change in total story size? Have you reduced it by 10%? Or maybe only 1%? If you're at the lower limit, it's more likely that you don't need to cut it so much as polish it a bit. Reducing the story size by 0.5% or something won't really improve it, but polishing presentation & pacing might. If you think you can cut 10% or 12% and still tell the story, then you probably do have some fat to cut, but maybe a balance of 5% cut and 5% polished up/rearranged might be the better approach.
